06948nam a22010935i 9781614518112DE-B159720211217065530.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211217t20142014gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2014020243  a(OCoLC)951149201  a97816145181127 a10.1515/97816145181122doi  a(DE-B1597)428044  a(OCoLC)893484664  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE00aP240.5b.I43 2014 4aP240.5 7aLAN0090002bisacsh0481pa490qDE-10100aIdentity Relations in Grammar /ced. by Kuniya Nasukawa, Henk Riemsdijk. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (371 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in Generative Grammar [SGG] ,x0167-4331 ;v1190 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFew concepts are as ubiquitous in the physical world of humans as that of identity. Laws of nature crucially involve relations of identity and non-identity, the act of identifying is central to most cognitive processes, and the structure of human language is determined in many different ways by considerations of identity and its opposite. The purpose of this book is to bring together research from a broad scale of domains of grammar that have a bearing on the role that identity plays in the structure of grammatical representations and principles. Beyond a great many analytical puzzles, the creation and avoidance of identity in grammar raise a lot of fundamental and hard questions. These include: Why is identity sometimes tolerated or even necessary, while in other contexts it must be avoided? What are the properties of complex elements that contribute to configurations of identity (XX)? What structural notions of closeness or distance determine whether an offending XX-relation exists or, inversely, whether two more or less distant elements satisfy some requirement of identity? Is it possible to generalize over the specific principles that govern (non-)identity in the various components of grammar, or are such comparisons merely metaphorical? Indeed, can we define the notion of identity in a formal way that will allow us to decide which of the manifold phenomena that we can think of are genuine instances of some identity (avoidance) effect? If identity avoidance is a manifestation in grammar of some much more encompassing principle, some law of nature, then how is it possible that what does and what does not count as identical in the grammars of different languages seems to be subject to considerable variation?  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aGenerative grammar. 0aGrammar, Comparative and generalxGrammatical categories. 0aIdentity (Philosophical concept) 0aIdentity (Philosophical concept). 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aAgreement.  aDoubling.  aIdentity Avoidance.  aObligatory Contour Principle (OCP).1 aAckema, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlexiadou, Artemis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBackley, Phillip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBye, Patrik, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHiraiwa, Ken, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnson, Kyle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLiao, Wei-wen Roger, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aManzini, M. Rita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNasukawa, Kuniya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNasukawa, Kuniya, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aOostendorp, Marc van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/